# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arrernte-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Humans first migrated to Australia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, and over time formed as many as 500 linguistic and territorial groups.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people once lived across large areas of the continental shelf that were later inundated by postglacial sea-level rise at the start of the Holocene inter-glacial period, reshaping coastal landscapes and separating Tasmania from the mainland.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people maintained extensive networks within the continent and certain groups maintained relationships with Torres Strait Islanders and the Makassar people of modern-day Indonesia.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Over the millennia, Aboriginal people developed complex trade networks, inter-cultural relationships, law and religions, which make up some of the oldest continuous cultures in the world.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] At the time of European colonisation of Australia, the Aboriginal people spoke more than 250 different languages, possessed varying degrees of technology, and lived in various types of settlements.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Languages (or dialects) and language-associated groups of people are connected with stretches of territory known as "Country", with which they have a profound spiritual connection.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Contemporary Aboriginal beliefs are shaped by traditional beliefs, the disruption of colonisation, religions brought to the continent by later migrants, and contemporary issues.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Just over half hold secular or other spiritual beliefs or no religious affiliation; about 40% are Christian; and about 1% adhere to a traditional Aboriginal religion.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Traditional cultural beliefs are passed down and shared through dancing, stories, songlines, and art that collectively weave an ontology of modern daily life and ancient creation known as the Dreaming.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Studies of Aboriginal groups' genetic makeup are ongoing, but evidence suggests that they have genetic inheritance from ancient Asian peoples.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians and Papuans shared the same paleocontinent Sahul, although they became genetically distinct about 37,000 years ago.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians have a broadly shared, complex genetic history, but only in the last 200 years have they been defined by others as, and started to self-identify as, a single group.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal identity has changed over time and place, with family lineage, self-identification, and community acceptance all of varying importance.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The 2021 census shows that there were 944,171 Aboriginal people, comprising 3.7% of Australia's population.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Over 80% of Aboriginal people today speak English at home, and about 77,000 speak an Indigenous language at home.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people, along with Torres Strait Islander people, suffer a number of severe health and economic deprivations in comparison with the wider Australian community.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Archeological evidence indicates that the ancestors of today's Aboriginal Australians first migrated to the continent 50,000 to 65,000 years ago.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] While there have been genomic studies placing arrival as late as 43,000 years ago, a 2025 study suggests that the peopling of Australia happened around 60,000 years ago, via two distinct routes.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Early human migration to Australia was achieved when it formed a part of the Sahul continent, connected to the island of New Guinea via a land bridge.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] This would have nevertheless required crossing the sea at the Wallace Line.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] It is also possible that people came by island-hopping via an island chain between Sulawesi and New Guinea, reaching North Western Australia via Timor.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] As sea levels rose, the people on the Australian mainland and nearby islands became increasingly isolated, some on Tasmania and some of the smaller offshore islands when the land was inundated at the start of the Holocene, the inter-glacial period that started about 11,700 years ago.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The modelling is based on data from archaeologists, anthropologists, ecologists, geneticists, climatologists, geomorphologists, and hydrologists.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The new models suggest that the first people may have landed in the Kimberley region in what is now Western Australia about 60,000 years ago, and had settled across the continent within 6,000 years.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians may have one of the oldest continuous cultures on earth.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] In Arnhem Land in the Northern Territory, oral histories comprising complex narratives have been passed down by Yolngu people through hundreds of generations.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The Aboriginal rock art, dated by modern techniques, shows that their culture has continued from ancient times.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Genetic studies have revealed that a population wave, termed East Eurasian Core, outgoing from the Iranian plateau during the Initial Upper Paleolithic period populated the Asia-Pacific region via a southern route dispersal.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] This wave is suggested to have expanded into the South and Southeast Asia region and subsequently diverged rapidly into the ancestors of Ancient Ancestral South Indians (AASI), Andamanese, East Asians, and Australasians, including Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians are genetically most closely related to other Oceanians, such as Papuans and Melanesians, who are collectively referred to as "Australasians," which can be described as "a deeply branching East Asian lineage".
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] This earlier group has been estimated to have possibly contributed around 2% ancestry to modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] 2017 found the bifurcation of Eastern Eurasians and Western Eurasians dates to at least 45,000 years ago, with indigenous Australians nested inside the Eastern Eurasian clade.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Genetic data on indigenous populations of Borneo and Malaysia showed them to be more closely related to other mainland Asian groups, than compared to the groups from Papua New Guinea and Australia.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] This indicates that populations in Australia were isolated for a long time from the rest of Southeast Asia.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] They remained untouched by migrations and population expansions into that area, which can be explained by the Wallace line.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The most common Y-chromosome haplogroups among Aboriginal Australians is C1b2, followed by haplogroups S and M; these latter haplogroups are also very frequent among Papuans.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] In a 2001 study, blood samples were collected from some Warlpiri people in the Northern Territory to study their genetic makeup (which is not representative of all Aboriginal peoples in Australia).
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The study concluded that the Warlpiri are descended from ancient Asians whose DNA is still somewhat present in Southeastern Asian groups, although greatly diminished.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The Warlpiri DNA lacks certain information found in modern Asian genomes, and carries information not found in other genomes.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] This reinforces the idea of ancient Aboriginal isolation.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Genetic data extracted in 2011 by Morten Rasmussen et al., who took a DNA sample from an early-20th-century lock of an Aboriginal person's hair, found that the Aboriginal ancestors probably migrated through South Asia and Maritime Southeast Asia, into Australia, where they stayed.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] As a result, outside of Africa, the Aboriginal peoples have continuously occupied the same territory longer than any other human populations.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] These findings suggest that modern Aboriginal Australians are the direct descendants of the eastern wave, who left Africa up to 75,000 years ago.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Examining DNA from a finger bone excavated in Siberia, researchers concluded that the Denisovans migrated from Siberia to tropical parts of Asia and that they interbred with modern humans in Southeast Asia 44,000 years BP, before Australia separated from New Guinea approximately 11,700 years BP.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] They contributed DNA to Aboriginal Australians and to present-day New Guineans and an indigenous tribe in the Philippines known as Mamanwa.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] This study confirms Aboriginal Australians as one of the oldest living populations in the world.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] They are possibly the oldest outside Africa, and they may have the oldest continuous culture on the planet.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] A 2016 study at the University of Cambridge suggests that it was about 50,000 years ago that these peoples reached Sahul (the supercontinent consisting of present-day Australia and its islands and New Guinea).
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The sea levels rose and isolated Australia about 10,000 years ago, but Aboriginal Australians and Papuans diverged from each other earlier, genetically, about 37,000 years BP, possibly because the remaining land bridge was impassable.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] This isolation makes the Aboriginal people the world's oldest culture.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The study also found evidence of an unknown hominin group, distantly related to Denisovans, with whom the Aboriginal and Papuan ancestors must have interbred, leaving a trace of about 4% in most Aboriginal Australians' genome.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] There is, however, increased genetic diversity among Aboriginal Australians based on geographical distribution.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] 2021 analysed a Holocene hunter-gatherer sample ("Leang Panninge") from South Sulawesi, which shares high amounts of genetic drift with Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] This suggests that a population split from the common ancestor of Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The sample also shows genetic affinity with East Asians and the Andamanese people of South Asia.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The authors note that this hunter-gatherer sample can be modelled with ~50% Australian/Papuan-related ancestry and either with ~50% East Asian or Andamanese Onge ancestry, highlighting the deep split between Leang Panninge and Aboriginal/Papuans.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] 2021 found that Philippines Negrito people split from the common ancestor of Aboriginal Australians and Papuans before the latter two diverged from each other, but after their common ancestor diverged from the ancestor of East Asian peoples.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Like Papuans, it's believed that Aboriginal Australians underwent a secondary admixture event with Altai-related Denisovan populations after they diverged from the ancestors of East Asians, who already mixed with Denisovans.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] This event was also separate from the admixture event experienced by Filipino Negritos, explaining why Aboriginal Australians and Papuans have relatively lower Denisovan ancestry.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Based on a reevaluation of mitogenomes, Gandini et al.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] 2025 proposed a "long chronology", which suggested an earlier settlement of Sahul by two migration routes about ~60 ka.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] One route came from northern Sunda via the Philippine archipelago whilst the other came from southern Sunda via Mainland Southeast Asia, with both routes ultimately tracing back to South Asia.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The settlers that undertook these routes were ancestral to populations indigenous to Australia, New Guinea and Oceania, and were also related to other East Eurasians instead of belonging to a separate wave.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The dingo reached Australia about 4,000 years ago.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Near that time, there were changes in language (with the Pama-Nyungan language family spreading over most of the mainland), and in stone tool technology.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The first type of evidence comes from a 2013 study by the Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology using large-scale genotyping data from a pool of Aboriginal Australians, New Guineans, island Southeast Asians, and Indians.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] It found that the New Guinea and Mamanwa (Philippines area) groups diverged from the Aboriginal about 36,000 years ago (there is supporting evidence that these populations are descended from migrants taking an early "southern route" out of Africa, before other groups in the area).
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Also the Indian and Australian populations mixed long before European contact, with this gene flow occurring during the Holocene (c.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The researchers had two theories for this: either some Indians had contact with people in Indonesia who eventually transferred those Indian genes to Aboriginal Australians, or a group of Indians migrated from India to Australia and intermingled with the locals directly.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] However, a 2016 study in *Current Biology* by Anders Bergström et al. excluded the Y chromosome as providing evidence for recent gene flow from India into Australia.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The study authors sequenced 13 Aboriginal Australian Y chromosomes using recent advances in gene sequencing technology.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] They investigated their divergence times from Y chromosomes in other continents, including comparing the haplogroup C chromosomes.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] They found a divergence time of about 54,100 years between the Sahul C chromosome and its closest relative C5, as well as about 54,300 years between haplogroups K*/M and their closest haplogroups R and Q.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The deep divergence time of 50,000-plus years with the South Asian chromosome and "the fact that the Aboriginal Australian Cs share a more recent common ancestor with Papuan Cs" excludes any recent genetic contact.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] They attributed the disparity between their results and previous findings to improvements in technology; none of the other studies had utilised complete Y chromosome sequencing, which has the highest precision.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] For example, use of a ten Y STRs method has been shown to massively underestimate divergence times.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Bergström's 2018 doctoral thesis looking at the population of Sahul suggests that other than relatively recent admixture, the populations of the region appear to have been genetically independent from the rest of the world since their divergence about 50,000 years ago.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] He writes "There is no evidence for South Asian gene flow to Australia ....
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians possess inherited abilities to adapt to a wide range of environmental temperatures in various ways.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] A study in 1958 comparing cold adaptation in the desert-dwelling Pitjantjatjara people compared with a group of European people showed that the cooling adaptation of the Aboriginal group differed from that of the Europeans, and that they were able to sleep more soundly through a cold desert night.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] A 2014 Cambridge University study found that a beneficial mutation in two genes that regulate thyroxine, a hormone involved in regulating body metabolism, helps to regulate body temperature in response to fever.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The effect of this is that the desert people are able to have a higher body temperature without accelerating the activity of the whole of the body, which can be especially detrimental in childhood diseases.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] This helps protect people to survive the side-effects of infection.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] It is estimated that the Indigenous Australian population at the time of first European settlement numbered at least 314,500 people.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Based on the 2021 census, the Australian Bureau of Statistics estimates there were 901,655 Aboriginal Australians, and 42,516 who identified as both Aboriginal Australian and Torres Strait Islander.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] These groups comprise 3.7% of the total Australian population.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] 39,538 people identified as Torres Strait Islander, which is a different ethnic group from Aboriginal Australian.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Based on initial 2021 census counts, the Aboriginal and Torres Strait islander population grew 25.2%, since the previous census in 2016.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Demographic factors – births, deaths and migration – accounted for 43.5% of the increase (71,086 people).
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] In turn, 76.2% of that increase was attributed to people aged 0–19 years in 2021, broken down as 52.5% for 0–4 year olds (births since 2016) and 23.7% for 5–19 year olds.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Reasons for the increase in Aboriginal population also include non-demographic factors.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] These include changes in individuals' identification as Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander in different censuses, and individuals completing a census form in 2021 but not in 2016.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] These factors accounted for 56.5% of the increase in the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander population.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Indigenous Australians (including Torres Strait Islanders) are less likely to live in the major Australian cities than are non-Indigenous Australians (41% compared with 73%).
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Although humans arrived in Australia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, it is possible that the ancestor language of existing Aboriginal languages is as recent as 12,000 years old.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Over 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] As of 2021, 84% of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders spoke only English at home.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018-19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use are endangered.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] According to the 2021 census, the classifiable Aboriginal languages with the most speakers are Kriol (7,403), Djambarrpuyngu (3,839), Pitjantjatjara (3,399), Warlpiri (2,592), Murrinh Patha (2,063) and Tiwi (2,053).
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] There were also over 10,000 people who spoke an Indigenous language that could not be further defined or classified.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] A number of English-based creoles have arisen in Australia after European contact, of which Kriol is among the strongest and fastest-growing Aboriginal languages.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Kriol is spoken in the Northern Territory and Western Australia.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] It is estimated that there are 20,000 to 30,000 speakers of Indigenous creole languages.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Before British colonisation, there were perhaps five to sixteen languages on Tasmania, possibly related to one another in four language families.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The last speaker of a traditional Tasmanian language, Fanny Cochrane Smith, died in 1905.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Palawa kani is an in-progress constructed language, built from a composite of surviving words from various Tasmanian Aboriginal languages.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Traditional Indigenous languages often incorporated sign systems to aid communication with the hearing impaired, to complement verbal communication, and to replace verbal communication when the spoken language was forbidden for cultural reasons.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Many of these sign systems are still in use.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Dispersing across the Australian continent over time, the ancient people expanded and differentiated into distinct groups, each with its own language and culture.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] More than 400 distinct Australian Aboriginal peoples have been identified, distinguished by names designating their ancestral languages, dialects, or distinctive speech patterns.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] According to noted anthropologist, archaeologist and sociologist Harry Lourandos, historically, these groups lived in three main cultural areas, the Northern, Southern and Central cultural areas.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The Northern and Southern areas, having richer natural marine and woodland resources, were more densely populated than the Central area.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Other group names are based on the language group or specific dialect spoken.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] These also coincide with geographical regions of varying sizes.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] However, these lists are neither exhaustive nor definitive, and there are overlaps.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Different approaches have been taken by non-Aboriginal scholars in trying to understand and define Aboriginal culture and societies, some focusing on the micro-level (tribe, clan, etc.), and others on shared languages and cultural practices spread over large regions defined by ecological factors.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Anthropologists have encountered many difficulties in trying to define what constitutes an Aboriginal people/community/group/tribe, let alone naming them.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Knowledge of pre-colonial Aboriginal cultures and societal groupings is still largely dependent on the observers' interpretations, which were filtered through colonial ways of viewing societies.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Some Aboriginal peoples identify as one of several saltwater, freshwater, rainforest or desert peoples.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The term *Aboriginal Australians* includes many distinct peoples who have developed across Australia for over 50,000 years.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] These peoples have a broadly shared, complex, genetic history, but it is only in the last two hundred years that they have been defined and have started to self-identify as a single group socio-politically.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] While some preferred the term *Aborigine* to *Aboriginal* in the past, as the latter was seen to have more directly discriminatory legal origins, use of the term *Aborigine* has declined in recent decades, as many consider the term an offensive and racist hangover from Australia's colonial era.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The definition of the term *Aboriginal* has changed over time and place, with family lineage, self-identification and community acceptance all being of varying importance.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The term *Indigenous Australians* refers to Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islander peoples, and the term is conventionally only used when both groups are included in the topic being addressed, or by self-identification by a person as Indigenous.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] As of 2021, 51% of Indigenous people stated that they held a secular or other spiritual belief or no religious affiliation; 41% were affiliated to Christianity; and 1% were affiliated to a traditional Aboriginal religion.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Australian Indigenous people have beliefs unique to each mob (tribe) and have a strong connection to the land.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Contemporary Indigenous Australian beliefs are a complex mixture, varying by region and individual across the continent.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] They are shaped by traditional beliefs, the disruption of colonisation, religions brought to the continent by Europeans, and contemporary issues.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Traditional cultural beliefs are passed down and shared by dancing, stories, songlines and art—especially Papunya Tula (dot painting)—collectively telling the story of creation known as The Dreamtime.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Additionally, traditional healers were also custodians of important Dreaming stories as well as their medical roles (for example the Ngangkari in the Western desert).
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Some core structures and themes are shared across the continent with details and additional elements varying between language and cultural groups.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] For example, in The Dreamtime of most regions, a spirit creates the earth then tells the humans to treat the animals and the earth in a way that is respectful to land.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] In Northern Territory this spirit is commonly said to be a huge snake or snakes that weaved its way through the earth and sky making the mountains and oceans.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] But in other places the spirits who created the world are known as wandjina rain and water spirits.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Major ancestral spirits include the Rainbow Serpent, Baiame, Dirawong and Bunjil.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Similarly, the Arrernte people of central Australia believed that humanity originated from great superhuman ancestors who brought the sun, wind and rain as a result of breaking through the surface of the Earth when waking from their slumber.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Many Dreamtime stories are still believed by many Indigenous Australians to this day.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Taken as a whole, Aboriginal Australians, along with Torres Strait Islander people, have a number of health and economic deprivations in comparison with the wider Australian community.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Due to the aforementioned disadvantage, Aboriginal Australian communities experience a higher rate of suicide, as compared to non-indigenous communities.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] These issues stem from a variety of different causes unique to indigenous communities, such as historical trauma, socioeconomic disadvantage, and decreased access to education and health care.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Also, this problem largely affects indigenous youth, as many indigenous youth may feel disconnected from their culture.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] To combat the increased suicide rate, many researchers have suggested that the inclusion of more cultural aspects into suicide prevention programs would help to combat mental health issues within the community.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Past studies have found that many indigenous leaders and community members, do in fact, want more culturally-aware health care programs.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Similarly, culturally-relative programs targeting indigenous youth have actively challenged suicide ideation among younger indigenous populations, with many social and emotional wellbeing programs using cultural information to provide coping mechanisms and improving mental health.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] Indigenous communities in remote Australia are often small, isolated towns with basic facilities, on traditionally owned land.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] These communities have between 20 and 300 inhabitants and are often closed to outsiders for cultural reasons.
[src:arrernte-language/aboriginal-australians] The long-term viability and resilience of Aboriginal communities in desert areas has been discussed by scholars and policy-makers.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] In linguistic typology, **nominative–accusative alignment** is a type of morphosyntactic alignment in which subjects of intransitive verbs are treated like subjects of transitive verbs, and are distinguished from objects of transitive verbs in basic clause constructions.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] Nominative–accusative alignment can be coded by case-marking, verb agreement and/or word order.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] It has a wide global distribution and is the most common alignment system among the world's languages (including English).
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] Languages with nominative–accusative alignment are commonly called **nominative–accusative languages**.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] A transitive verb is associated with two noun phrases (or arguments): a subject and a direct object.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] An intransitive verb is associated with only one argument, a subject.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] The different kinds of arguments are usually represented as **S**, **A**, and **O**.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] **S** is the sole argument of an intransitive verb, **A** is the subject (or most agent-like) argument of a transitive verb, and **O** is the direct object (or most patient-like) argument of a transitive verb.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] This is in contrast with ergative–absolutive alignment, where **S** is coded in the same way as **O**, while **A** receives distinct marking, or tripartite alignment, where **A**, **S** and **O** all are coded in a different manner.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] It is common for languages (such as Georgian and Hindustani) to have overlapping alignment systems, which exhibit both nominative–accusative and ergative–absolutive coding, a phenomenon called split ergativity.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] In fact, there are relatively few languages that exhibit only ergative–absolutive alignment (called pure ergativity) and tend to be isolated in certain regions of the world, such as the Caucasus, parts of North America and Mesoamerica, the Tibetan Plateau, and Australia.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] Such languages include Sumerian, Standard Tibetan, and Mayan.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] Nominative–accusative alignment can manifest itself in visible ways, called coding properties.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] Often, these visible properties are morphological and the distinction will appear as a difference in the actual morphological form and spelling of the word, or as case particles (pieces of morphology) which will appear before or after the word.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] If a language exhibits morphological case marking, arguments S and A will appear in the nominative case and argument O will appear in the accusative case, or in a similar case such as the oblique.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] There may be more than one case fulfilling the accusative role; for instance, Finnish marks objects with the partitive or the accusative to contrast telicity.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] It is highly common for only accusative arguments to exhibit overt case marking while nominative arguments exhibit null (or absent) case markings.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] In Modern English, case marking is only found with first and (non-neuter) third person pronouns, which have distinct subject and object forms.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] Not all arguments are equally likely to exhibit overt case marking.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] In languages with nominative–accusative alignment, it is common to divide direct objects into two classes (with respect to overt case marking), a phenomenon called ‘differential object marking’ by Bossong (1985).
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] Some languages code very little through morphology and are more dependent on syntax to encode meaning and grammatical relationships.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] If a language relies less on overt case marking, alignment may be coded through word order, as in this example from Indonesian.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] In the following example from French, all subjects, both S and A, appear before the verb while O appears after the verb.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] Arguments occurring before the verb are coded as nominative, while arguments occurring directly after the verb are coded as accusative.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] Alternatively, alignment can also manifest visibly through agreement on the verb.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] In the following example from Amharic, the verb can be head-marked for S, A, and O.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] Both S in the intransitive clause and A in the transitive clause are marked by the same affix (*-ə* ‘3SG.M’), while O in the transitive clause is marked by a different affix (*-w* ‘3SG.M.O’).
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] English has residual verb agreement with nominative–accusative alignment, which is only manifest with third person singular S and A in present tense.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] Nominative–accusative alignment can also be distinguished through behavioral properties, in the way a nominative or accusative argument will behave when placed in particular syntactic constructions.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] This has to do with the impact of alignment on the level of the whole sentence rather than the individual word.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] Morphosyntactic alignment determines which arguments can be omitted in a coordinate structure during the process of conjunction reduction (deleting arguments from the ends of joined clauses).
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] In nominative–accusative, only arguments S and A can be omitted and not argument O.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] The omitted subject argument of the embedded clause must correspond to the subject (nominative) of the matrix-clause.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] If it corresponds to the object (accusative), the sentence is ungrammatical.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] Here the omitted argument of the embedded clause corresponds to the direct object (absolutive) of the matrix-clause.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] If it corresponds to the subject (ergative), the sentence is ungrammatical.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] The alignment system also impacts the triggering and realization of other such syntactic processes as raising constructions, subject-controlled subject deletion and object-controlled subject deletion.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] Languages exhibiting accusative alignment are the most widespread of all of the alignment types.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] These languages can be found on every continent, in comparison to languages with ergative alignment that are restricted to certain areas of the world, namely the Caucasus, parts of North American and Mesoamerica, the Tibetan plateau, and Australia.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] One of the ways in which the production of a nominative–accusative case marking system can be explained is from an Optimality Theoretic perspective.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] Case marking is said to fulfill two functions, or constraints: an identifying function and a distinguishing function.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] The identifying function is exemplified when case morphology encodes (identifies) specific semantic, thematic, or pragmatic properties or information about the nominal argument.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] Accusative case in the position of the direct object, for example, can be a strong identifier of patienthood.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] The distinguishing function is used to distinguish between the core arguments, the subject and the object, of a transitive clause.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] It is rare for case to serve only the distinguishing function, which overlaps greatly with the ‘identify’ function.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] Other ways of disambiguating the arguments of a transitive predicate (subject agreement, word order restriction, context, intonation, etc.) may explain this cross-linguistic observation.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] De Hoop and Malchukov argue that case systems that are completely based on the identification function must be richer in case morphology compared to languages based mainly on the distinguishing function.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] One theory that has been posited to account for the occurrence of accusative systems is that of functional pressure.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] When applied to languages, this theory operates around the various needs and pressures on a speech community.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] It has been suggested that languages have evolved to suit the needs of their users.These communities will develop some functional system to meet the needs that they have.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] So, it has been proposed that the accusative system arose from a functional pressure to avoid ambiguity and make communication a simpler process.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] It is useful for languages to have a means of distinguishing between subjects and objects, and between arguments A, S, and O.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] This is helpful so that sentences like "Tom hit Fred" cannot be interpreted as "Fred hit Tom." Tripartite alignment systems accomplish this differentiation by coding S, A and O all differently.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] However, this is not structurally economical, and tripartite systems are comparatively rare, but to have all arguments marked the same makes the arguments too ambiguous.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] Alongside the principle of distinguishability seems to operate a principle of economy.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] It is more efficient to have as few cases as possible without compromising intelligibility.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] In this way the dual pressures of efficiency and economy have produced a system which patterns two kinds of arguments together a third separately.
[src:arrernte-language/accusative-language] Both accusative and ergative systems use this kind of grouping to make meaning clearer.
[src:arrernte-language/adithinngithigh-language] However, it is not clear how distinct the two varieties are.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] The **Adnyamathanha language** (pronounced /ˈɑːdnjəmʌdənə/), also known as **yura ngarwala** natively and **Kuyani**, also known as **Guyani** and other variants, are two closely related Australian Aboriginal languages.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] They are traditional languages of the Adnyamathanha of and the Kuyani peoples, of the Flinders Ranges and to the west of the Flinders respectively, in South Australia.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] As of the 2021 Australian census, there were around 262 speakers of Adnyamathanha, up from 140 in 2016, making it an endangered language; there have been no speakers of Kuyani recorded since 1975.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] The first bilingual dictionary of the language was published in November 2020.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] The name of the witchetty grub comes from Adnyamathanha.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] Guyani is also spelled *Kijani, Kuyani, Kwiani*.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] Dixon classifies Adnyamathanha and Guyani as a single language, Ethnologue, Glottolog and AIATSIS treats them as separate languages, L10: Adnyamathanha and L9: Kuyani.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] Estimates of the number of people who speak Adnyamathanha are variable, though it is a severely endangered language.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] According to Oates (1973) there were only 30 speakers, around 20 according to Schmidt in 1990, 127 in the 1996 Australian census, 140 in the 2016 census and 262 in 2021.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] Adjnjamathanha and Guyani have the same phonemic inventory.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] Most of the nasals and laterals are allophonically prestopped.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] While the closely related Guyani retains word-initial stops, Adnyamathanha has undergone systematic lenition of stops in this position.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] Former *p has become [v], former *t̪ and probably also *c have become /j/, and former *k has disappeared entirely.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] Adnyamathanha has a complex system of personal pronouns.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] There are 10 different ways of saying we "you and I" (first person dual), depending on the relationship between the speaker and the addressee.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] The linguist Bernhard Schebeck travelled to the Nepabunna region in the 1970s, and wrote *An Adnyamathanha-English Research Dictionary* in 2000, which was "For private, or internal, use only – not for publication".
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] Dorothy Tunbridge, a linguist from Canberra and author of *Flinders Ranges Dreaming* visited the area in the 1980s.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] Both contributed much to knowledge of the language, but neither recorded all of the words that were known to local speakers.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] In November 2020 the first-ever bilingual Adnyamathanha/English dictionary and grammar was published, with translations from and to each language.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] Compiled by Terrence Coulthard and his wife Josephine, the 400-page *Adnyamathanha Culture Guide and Language Book* includes descriptions of cultural practices, songlines (*muda*), the Adnyamathanha kinship system and social history.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] Terrence, an Adnyamathanha speaker, had been collecting information on the culture and language for 40 years, building on the earlier work by Schebeck and Tunbridge.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] Linguists and others from the University of Adelaide's Mobile Language Team helped the couple to finalise work on the book in the 18 months to two years before publication.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] The Coulthards run Iga Warta, a cultural tourism enterprise, located near Nepabunna in the Gammon Ranges, the site of a mission where Terrence grew up.
[src:arrernte-language/adnyamathanha-language] Iga Warta means "native orange", named by 19th-century English botanist John Lindley as *Capparis mitchelii*.
[src:arrernte-language/aghu-tharrnggala-language] Aghu Tharrnggala is demonstrably related to Kuku-Thaypan and Rarmul.
[src:arrernte-language/aghu-tharrnggala-language] The two may also have been related to Takalak, although there is insufficient information for this to be certain.
[src:arrernte-language/aghu-tharrnggala-language] The consonant phonemes of Aghu Tharrnggala are located in the chart below.
[src:arrernte-language/alawa-language] Alawa has a typical consonant inventory for an Indigenous Australian language, with five contrastive places of articulation, multiple lateral consonants, and no voicing contrast among the stops.
[src:arrernte-language/alawa-language] Note: there are no standardised IPA symbols for alveopalatal stops.
[src:arrernte-language/alawa-language] The vowel system of Alawa is made up of four vowel phonemes: the high front vowel /i/, the high back vowel /u/, the mid front vowel /e/, and the low central vowel /a/.
[src:arrernte-language/alawa-language] There are no rounding contrasts or length contrasts in this language.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] A member of the Western Arrernte people, Namatjira was born and raised at the remote Hermannsburg Lutheran Mission, 126 km west-southwest from Alice Springs.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] He showed interest in art from an early age but it was not until 1934 (aged 32) and under the guidance of Rex Battarbee that he began to paint seriously.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Namatjira's richly detailed, Western art-influenced watercolours of the outback departed significantly from the abstract designs and symbols of traditional Aboriginal art, and inspired the Hermannsburg School of painting.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] He became a household name in Australia and reproductions of his works hung in many homes throughout the nation.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] In 1956, a portrait of Namatjira by William Dargie became the first of an Aboriginal person to win the Archibald Prize.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Namatjira was awarded the Queen's Coronation Medal in 1953, and was honoured with an Australian postage stamp in 1968.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Namatjira was the first recorded Northern Territory Aboriginal person to be freed from restrictions that made Aboriginal people wards of the state when he was granted full rights of citizenship in 1957.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] This gave him the right to vote in national, state and territory elections, gave him freedom of movement and freed him from restrictions on buying alcohol; but, in the Northern Territory, he still had limited land rights.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] However, Namatjira remained poorly treated by the government; he was sentenced to prison after leaving a bottle of rum on the back seat of his car, which was likely taken and consumed by a man who had then drunkenly beaten and killed his own wife.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Public and international outcry intervened in the liability ruling and Namatjira instead served less than two months in a native reserve in Papunya.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] He continued to live in Papunya with his wife, until he died of heart disease in an Alice Springs hospital in 1959.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Described as a "monumental figure" within Australian art, Namatjira is considered one of the most talented Arrernte artists to have lived.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] They form the artistic and memorial collective the Namatjira project, which includes his Ramsay Prize and Archibald Prize-winning great-grandson Vincent Namatjira.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] He was born at Hermannsburg Mission, Ntaria, in Alice Springs in 1902, the son of Jonathan Namatjira .
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Namatjira was raised on the Hermannsburg Mission and baptised after his parents' adoption of Christianity.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] He was born as Elea, but once baptised, they changed his name to Albert.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] As a child, he sketched what he saw around him.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] When he was 18 years old, he left the mission and married his wife Ilkalita, a Kukatja woman, who was christened Rubina upon their return to Hermannsburg.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] His wife, like his father's wife, was from the wrong skin group and he violated the law of his people by marrying outside the classificatory kinship system.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] In 1928 he was ostracised for several years in which he worked as a camel driver and saw much of Central Australia, which he was later to depict in his paintings.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] He also worked as a blacksmith, carpenter and stockman, at the mission and at the surrounding cattle stations.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] He was a cousin of Aboriginal country music star Gus Williams, and is credited with bringing music into Williams' life.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Namatjira was introduced to western-style painting through a charity art exhibition in 1933, which raised the money to bring fresh water to his hometown of Hermannsburg.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] The exhibition was run by Violet Teague, whom Namatjira admired enough to name his daughter after, and her sister Una.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] In 1934, Namatjira met Rex Battarbee and John Gardner, who had an exhibition at his mission.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Battarbee returned to the area in the winter of 1936 to paint the landscape, and Namatjira, expressing an interest in learning to paint, acted as his cameleer and guide to show him local scenic areas.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Namatjira started painting in a unique style.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] His landscapes normally highlighted both the rugged geological features of the land in the background, and the distinctive Australian flora in the foreground with very old, stately and majestic white gum trees surrounded by twisted scrub.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] His work had a high quality of illumination showing the gashes of the land and the twists in the trees.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] His colours were similar to the ochres that his ancestors had used to depict the same landscape, but his style was appreciated by Europeans because it met the aesthetics of western art.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] In his early career, Namatjira's work included tjuringa (sacred object) designs, biblical themes and figurative subjects, and he also carved and painted various artefacts.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] In 1937 Friedrich Albrecht, superintendent of Hermannsburg, took ten of Namatjira's watercolours with him to a Lutheran conference at Nuriootpa, South Australia, and Battarbee put three of his paintings in an exhibition with the Royal South Australian Society of Arts in Adelaide.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] In 1938, Namatjira held his first solo exhibition in Melbourne.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] He became the first prominent Aboriginal artist to work in a contemporary western style, and thus regarded as an example of assimilation.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] In 1944 he was included in *Who's Who in Australia*.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Subsequent exhibitions in Sydney and Adelaide also sold out.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] His work garnered wide acclaim, both in Australia and in other countries.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Queen Elizabeth II became one of his more notable fans and he was awarded the Queen's Coronation Medal in 1953 and met her in Canberra in 1954.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] He was elected an honorary member of the Royal Art Society of New South Wales in 1955.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Not only did his own art become widely recognised, but a painting of him by William Dargie won the Archibald Prize in 1956, the first painting of an Aboriginal person to win the prize.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Namatjira's artworks were colourful and varied depictions of the Australian landscape.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] One of his first landscapes from 1936, *Central Australian Landscape*, shows a land of rolling green hills.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Another early work, *Ajantzi Waterhole* (1937), shows a close up view of a small waterhole, with Namatjira capturing the reflection in the water.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] The landscape becomes one of contrasting colours, a device that is often used by Western painters, with red hills and green trees in *Red Bluff* (1938).
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] *Central Australian Gorge* (1940) shows detailed rendering of rocks and reflections in the water.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] In *Flowering Shrubs* Namatjira contrasts the blossoming flowers in the foreground with the more barren desert and cliffs in the background.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Namatjira's love of trees was often described so that his paintings of trees were more portraits than landscapes, which is shown in the portrait of the often depicted ghost gum in *Ghost Gum Glen Helen* (c.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] His unique style of painting was denounced soon after his death by some critics as being a product of his assimilation into western culture, rather than his own connection to his subject matter or his natural style.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] This view has, however, been largely abandoned.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Although Namatjira's paintings appear similar to conventional European landscapes, his work was imbued with his feeling for country and sacred sites.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] He used repetition, intricate patterns and high horizons to blend the styles of the two worlds he lived in.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] In 2022, Namatjira's work enjoyed a surge in popularity that exceeded the general increased interest in Australian art at this time.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] *Glen Helen Gorge* sold for more than A$120,000 in Melbourne, and in July *The Granseur – Mount Sonda* fetched A$54,000 in Adelaide.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] The latter was a record price, achieving nearly A$10,000 more than had been expected.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Due to his wealth, Namatjira soon found himself the subject of humbugging, a ritualised form of begging.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Arrernte are expected to share everything they own, and as Namatjira's income grew, so did his extended family.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] At one time he was singlehandedly providing for over 600 people with financial support.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] To ease the burden on his strained resources, Namatjira sought to lease a cattle station to benefit his extended family.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Originally granted, the lease was subsequently rejected because the land was part of a returned servicemen's ballot, and also because he had no ancestral claim on the property.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] He then tried to build a house in Alice Springs, but was cheated in his land dealings.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] The land he was sold was on a flood plain and was unsuitable for building.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Despite the fact that he was held as one of Australia's greatest artists, Namatjira was living in poverty.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] His plight became a media *cause célèbre*, resulting in a wave of public outrage.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] In 1957 the government exempted Namatjira and his wife from the restrictive legislation that applied to Aboriginal people in the Northern Territory.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Namatjira was encouraged to apply for full rights of citizenship at 55 years of age, allowing him to vote, own land, build a house and buy alcohol unlike other Indigenous Australians in the Northern Territory.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] He was then exempt from classification as an 'Aboriginal' for the purposes of the *Welfare Ordinance 1953*.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] This did not mean that he was legally *not* an Aboriginal, as some sources mistakenly suggest.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] However, his adult children and other relatives remained as "wards" under the *Welfare Ordinance 1953*.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Although Albert and Rubina were legally allowed to drink alcohol, his Aboriginal family and friends were not.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] This artificial social divide and the Arrernte culture that expected him to share everything he owned brought Namatjira into conflict with the law.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] When an Aboriginal woman, Fay Iowa, was killed at Morris Soak, Namatjira was held responsible by stipendiary magistrate, Jim Lemaire, for bringing alcohol into the camp.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] He was reprimanded at the coronial inquest.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] In the Northern Territory at that time, it was against the law to supply alcohol to an Aboriginal person.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Namatjira was charged with leaving a bottle of rum in a place, i.e. on a car seat, where a clan brother and fellow Hermannsburg artist Henoch Raberaba, could get access to it.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Convicted for an offence under the *Welfare Ordinance 1953*, for supplying an Aboriginal (a "ward") with liquor, he was sentenced to six months in prison.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Namatjira appealed against the conviction to the Supreme Court of the Northern Territory (with his defence supported by the Council for Aboriginal Rights in Victoria).
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] The Supreme Court upheld the conviction but reduced the sentence from six to three months.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] The High Court of Australia refused an application to appeal.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] There was widespread sympathy for Namatjira and negative publicity about the operation of the Ordinance across Australia and abroad.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] After the public uproar, the Minister for Territories, Paul Hasluck, intervened and the sentence was served at Papunya Native Reserve.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] He was released after only serving two months due to medical and humanitarian reasons.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Despondent after his incarceration, Namatjira continued to live with Rubina in a cottage at Papunya, where he suffered a heart attack.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] There is evidence that Albert believed that he had the bone pointed at him by a member of Fay Iowa's family (this idea of being "sung" to death was also held by Frank Clune, a popular travel writer, Aboriginal activist and organiser of Albert's whirlwind 1956 trip).
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] After being transferred to Alice Springs hospital, Namatjira astonished his mentor Rex Battarbee by presenting him with three landscapes, with a promise of more to come; a promise unrealised.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Namatjira died soon after of heart disease complicated by pneumonia on 8 August 1959 in Alice Springs.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] At the time of his death Namatjira had painted a total of around 2,000 paintings.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] He is hailed today as one of the greatest Australian artists and a pioneer for Aboriginal rights.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Namatjira's work is on public display in some of Australia's major art galleries.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] The Art Gallery of New South Wales now displays a number of Namatjira's work, although Hal Missingham, then Director of the gallery, initially rejected his work, saying: "We'll consider his work when it comes up to scratch".
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Two years before his death, part of Namatjira's copyright was sold to a company in exchange for royalties.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] After his death, Albert Namatjira's copyright was sold by the public trustee in 1983 for A$8,500, despite Namatjira's will leaving his copyright to his widow and children.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] The copyright was returned to the family's Albert Namatjira Trust in an October 2017 deal enabled by a donation by philanthropist Dick Smith, in the name of art dealer John Brackenreg, who was seen as having acquired the rights to Namatjira's art in 1957 in an act of exploitation.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Namatjira was honoured on postage stamps issued by Australia Post in 1968, again in 1993 with examples of his work, and in the Namatjira Centenary stamp series in 2002.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] The Northern Territory electoral division of Namatjira, which surrounds Alice Springs, was renamed in 2012 from MacDonnell, in honour of Namatjira.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] State Route 2, west of Alice Springs, is named Namatjira Drive after Namatjira, as is Namatjira Park in Clayton, Victoria.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] In January 2013, two gum trees that featured prominently in Namatjira's watercolours were destroyed in an arson attack, while they were in the process of being heritage-listed, in an "appalling and a tragic act of cultural vandalism".
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] In 2015, the Twin Gums site was again nominated for heritage listing.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] A number of biographical films have been made about Namatjira (at least three before his death), including the 1947 documentary *Namatjira the Painter*.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Namatjira has been the subject of numerous songs.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Country star Slim Dusty was the first artist to record a tribute song, "Namatjira", in the 1960s, and Rick and Thel Carey followed up with their tribute "The Stairs That Namatjira Climbed" in 1963.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] He appeared as himself in the feature film *The Phantom Stockman*.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] The Namatjira Project was a community cultural development project launched in 2009 that included an award-winning theatre production by Big hART focusing on Namatjira's life and work.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] On 28 July 2017, Google commemorated Namatjira's 115th birthday with a featured Doodle for Australian users, acknowledging his substantial contributions to the art and culture of Australia.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] A number of Albert Namatjira's descendants paint at the *Iltja Ntjarra - Many Hands* art centre in Alice Springs.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Vincent Namatjira, Albert Namatjira's great-grandson, is a well-known artist in his own right, winning the A$100,000 Ramsay Art Prize in 2019.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Vincent's 2014 series, *Albert's Story*, reflects on Albert Namatjira's life and legacy.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] About the series, Vincent has stated: "I hope my grandfather would be quite proud, maybe smiling down on me; because I won't let him go.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] I just keep carrying him on, his name and our families' stories." The series comprises 13 artworks, telling the story of Albert's life.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Vincent's work was also shortlisted for the Archibald Prize in 2017, 2018 and 2019 and won the prize in 2020.
[src:arrernte-language/albert-namatjira] Vincent's 2021 book about his great-grandfather, featuring artworks from *Albert's Story*, was shortlisted for a 2022 Australian Book Industry Award in the "Small Publishers' Children's Book of the Year" category.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] There are about 4,100 speakers of **Eastern**/**Central Arrernte**, making this dialect one of the widest spoken of any Indigenous language in Australia, the one usually referred to as Arrernte and the one described in detail below.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] It is spoken in the Alice Springs area and taught in schools and universities, heard in media and used in local government.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] The second biggest dialect in the group is Alyawarre.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] Some of the other dialects are spoken by very few people, leading to efforts to revive their usage; others are now completely extinct.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] "Aranda" is a simplified, Australian English approximation of the traditional pronunciation of the name of *Arrernte* [ˈarəɳ͡ɖa].
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] The Arrernte also have a highly developed Arrernte sign language, also known as Iltyeme-iltyeme.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] There is also an Anmatyerr sign language called *iltyem-iltyem* which is used by many Anmatyerr speakers to communicate non-verbally; the word iltja means 'hand, finger' and the term translates as 'signaling with hands'.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] Sign language is used when Anmatyerr people when hunting, when talking to the deaf, when somebody passes away and when talking to elders.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] The Alice Springs Language Centre delivers language teaching at primary, middle and senior schools, offering Arrernte, Indonesian, Japanese, Spanish and Chinese.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] There are two courses teaching Arrernte at tertiary level: at the Batchelor Institute and at Charles Darwin University.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] There are books available in Arandic languages in the Living Archive of Aboriginal Languages.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] Projects are being run to revive dying dialects of the language, such as Southern Arrernte/Pertame.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] This description relates to Central or Eastern Arrernte.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] Apart from /w/ and /ɰ ~ ʁ̞/, which are in contrastive distribution, all consonants have labialized forms in complementary distribution, considered to be dependent on consonant position. /ɰ ~ ʁ̞/ is described as velar [ɰ] by Breen & Dobson (2005), and as uvular [ʁ̞] by Henderson (2003).
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] The tap is occasionally a trill, especially when emphasized, but may also be weakened.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] The prenasalized series are not included in Breen & Dobson (2005), but are treated as consonant sequences.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] Prenasalized stops are voiced throughout; prestopped nasals are voiceless during the stop.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] The vowel system of Eastern/Central Arrernte is unusual in that there are only two contrastive vowel phonemes, /a/ and /ə/.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] Two-vowel systems are very rare worldwide, but are also found in some Northwest Caucasian languages.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] It seems that the vowel system derives from an earlier one with more phonemes, but after the development of labialised consonants in the vicinity of round vowels, the vowels lost their roundedness/backness distinction, merging into just two phonemes.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] There is little allophonic variation in different consonantal contexts for the vowels.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] Instead, the phonemes can be realised by various different articulations in free variation.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] For example, the phoneme /ə/ can be pronounced [ɪ ~ e ~ ə ~ ʊ] in most contexts.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] However, it is required to be [ʊ] when phrase-initial before a labialized consonant (see below).
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] The underlying syllable structure of Eastern/Central Arrernte is argued to be VC(C), with obligatory codas and no onsets.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] Underlying phrase-initial /ə/ is realised as zero, except before a rounded consonant where, by a rounding process of general applicability, it is realised as [ʊ].
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] It is also common for phrases to carry a final [ə] corresponding to no underlying segment.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] Among the evidence for this analysis is that some suffixes have suppletive variants for monosyllabic and bisyllabic bases.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] Stems that appear monosyllabic and begin with a consonant in fact select the bisyllabic variant.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] Stress falls on the first nucleus preceded by a consonant, which by this analysis can be stated more uniformly as the second underlying syllable.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] And the frequentative is formed by reduplicating the final VC syllable of the verb stem; it does not include the final [ə].
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] Eastern and Central Arrernte has fairly free word order but tends towards SOV.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] It is generally ergative, but is accusative in its pronouns.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] Pronouns may be marked for duality and skin group.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] Body parts normally require non-possessive pronouns (inalienable possession), though younger speakers may use possessives in this case too (e.g.
[src:arrernte-language/arrernte-language] *akaperte ayenge* or *akaperte atyinhe* 'my head').
